 consumption in Peru.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E018750/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The research explores how consumption impacts on people?s wellbeing in seven poor Peruvian communities. It draws on social science literature on consumption and incorporates the key factors highlighted by studies on wellbeing determinants. &lt;br />&lt;br />Generally, it is accepted that consumption increases wellbeing by lifting people out of poverty and that it has a negative impact if it fails to place them at a higher social position. However, other aspects defining consumption such as the symbolic meaning of goods, its pleasurable dimension, the role of goods and services as basic needs satisfiers, etc. have not been systematically tackled. This research incorporates those aspects through the concepts of 'motives' and 'satisfiers' using a multi-methods approach. &lt;br />&lt;br />It draws on psychologists? claim that motives are important in understanding the linkages between wellbeing and people?s behaviour. It also integrates the work of human needs theorists stressing the importance of analysing the effectiveness of goods and services as basic needs satisfiers. It finds, that people consuming because of hedonic reasons are happier, but those consuming for social acceptance and higher status are not. Moreover, being motivated by basic needs has a negative impact on happiness. The reason might lie in the type of satisfiers used. The exploratory study of satisfiers in a Peruvian slum points at their inefficiency, which might be the root of people?s frustration through consumption. &lt;/p> 
